Five of the new schools are especially noteworthy.

'!. The SCHOOL OF Si: IGNATIUS makes a specialty of active, energetic arid practical spiritual life aiming at forming the will for personal sanctification and apostolic work. -

St. Ignatius (1491, 1495-1556) : founder of the Society of Jesus; Exercitia spirittialia, new ed. Madrid, 1919. There are many English versions, for example those of Morris and of Joseph Rickaby. The Exercises comprise a 'method of procedure for reformings. son and for transforming'^, to conformity with the divine model, Jesus Christ. ' 7 '"The work," says Father Watrigant (Etudes religieuses, vol. cix, p. 134), "condenses a vast movement of. spirit and of thought which had slowly been developed during the preceding centuries. It is the starting point of a flood .of- spiritual life that has since the sixteenth century been constantly rising," wave on wave, and it is likewise the point of convergence for diverse currents coursing through, the Middle Ages and finding their beginnings in the earliest days of Christianity. "

Fully to understand the spirit of St. Ignatius, one should read the Consti- , tutions and Letters (Epistolee, 12 vols., M. H. S. J., 1904-1918). Cfr. also Thompson, F., St. Ignatius Loyola, New-York, 1909; Rose, S.', St. Ignatius ' Loyola and the Early Jesuits, New-York, 1896*; Pise, C. C., St. Ignatius, S.J., New- York, 1845; Mariani, F., Life of St. Ignatius Loyola, Founder of the Jestdts, Eng. tr. Faber, 2 vols., London, 1848; Joly, II., St. Ignatius, (tr.), London; Washbourne, .1899; Bartoli, D., History of St. Ignatius of Loyola, 2 vols., New-York, 1855; also, life by Pollen, 1922; Sedgwick, H. D., Ignatitts Loyola, London and New- York .: Macmillan, 1923; Spiritual Exercises of St. Ignatius, Eng. tr. fr. Spanish, ed. Lattey, St. Louis: Herder, '1928; Spiritual Exercises tr. from the Autograph, Eng. tr. Mullan, New- York, 1814; Trans, and Commentary on Spiritual Exercises, Rickaby, J., London : Burns and Gates, 1915; Bernhardt, W., Die vier Zentralsideen des Exerzi- tiensbuches de hi. Ignatiiis, Ratisbon : Habbel, c. 1928; Codina, A., Los origenes de las Ejercidos de S. Ignado de Loyola, Barcelona, 1926; Watrigant, H.', La genese des exercices de S.Ignace, Amiens, 1897, and La meditation fondamentale avant S. Ignace, Enghien, 1907; Brou, A., La spiri- tualite de S. Ignace, Paris : Beauchesne, 1914, and S. Ignace, Maitre d'of-aison, Paris : Ed. Spes, 1925; Spirittial Exercises of St. Ignatius of Loyola, Eng. tr. with Directorium and Commentary, Longride (Anglican), London : R. Scott, 1919; Redman, J., Soldier's Companion to the Spiritual Exercises, London : Burns and Gates, c. l882 2 ; Curtis, J., Way of Perfection in the Spiritual Exercises of St. Ignatius of Loyola, Dublin : Gill, c. 1882; Meditations on Life and Virtues of St. Ignatius of Lovola, Eng. tr. M. A. W., London : Burns and Gates, New- York : Catholic Pub. Soc., c. 1888.

