ART. III. THE OBLIGATION INCUMBENT UPON PRIESTS OF TENDING TO PERFECTION *

377. Priests in virtue of their functions and of the mission which makes theirs the duty of sanctifying souls, are bound to a higher interior holiness than that of the simple religious not raised .to the priesthood. This is the express teaching of St. Thomas, 2 confirmed by the most authoritative ecclesiastical pronouncements. The Councils, and particularly that of Trent, 3 the Supreme Pontiffs, and especially Leo XIII 4 and Pius X, 5 so insist upon the necessity of holiness in the priest, that to deny our thesis is to stand in open contradiction to authorities that cannot be gainsaid. Let it suffice to recall the fact that Pius X, upon the occasion of the fiftieth anniversary of his priesthood, issued a letter addressed to the Catholic clergy, wherein he shows the necessity of holiness in the priest, and enumerates one by one the means necessary to attain it, those very means, by the way, which are insisted on in our Seminaries. After describing interior holiness ( vita mommque sancti- monia),he declares that only this holiness makes us what our vocation requires us. to be, "men who are crucified to the world, who have put on the new Adam, men whose thoughts are fixed on heavenly things and who strive by all possible means to lead others to heaven."

378. The New Code has confirmed the views of Pius X by emphasizing more than the old legislation did the neces- sity of holiness in the priest and the means of exercising himself therein. It declares in no obscure words that

