or the prayer of Divine Delights, because it is here that for die first time the presence of God "is felt by a kind of spiritual delight; in her Life (C. XIV) she calls it the prayer of quiet- and she explains it by the second way of watering the garden. Other writers call it the -prayer of silence, pre- cisely because the soul then ceases to reason.

